  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Anaerobic\nprotozoan\nparasites\nFound in the human gastrointestinal tract\n[1]\nMost common eukaryotic parasites found in human stool\nControversial if they are a commensal organism or a pathogen",
      "subsections": {
        "Epidemiology": {
          "text": "Have been found worldwide\nReside in the cecum and colon of both children in adults\nHave also been found in various animals (including pigs, monkeys, rodents, and poultry)\nPrevalence is geographically variable, but generally higher in developing countries",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Transmission": {
          "text": "Mode of transmission is not fully understood, but though to be fecal-oral\n[2]",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Microbiology": {
          "text": "Vary in size between 5 and 40 micrometers\nLack a cell wall\nHave mitochondria, golgi apparatus, smooth and rough endoplasmic reticula\nTypically reproduce by binary fission\nGrow in anaerobic culture conditions",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
      "tables": [],
